A string can be abbreviated by replacing any number of non-adjacent, non-empty substrings with their lengths. The lengths should not have leading zeros.

For example, a string such as "substitution" could be abbreviated as (but not limited to):

"s10n" ("s ubstitutio n")
"sub4u4" ("sub stit u tion")
"12" ("substitution")
"su3i1u2on" ("su bst i t u ti on")
"substitution" (no substrings replaced)
The following are not valid abbreviations:

"s55n" ("s ubsti tutio n", the replaced substrings are adjacent)
"s010n" (has leading zeros)
"s0ubstitution" (replaces an empty substring)
Given a string word and an abbreviation abbr, return whether the string matches the given abbreviation.

A substring is a contiguous non-empty sequence of characters within a string.

class Solution {
    public boolean validWordAbbreviation(String word, String abbr) {
        int pt1 = 0;
        int pt2 = 0;
        //use tow pointers to track current position in two strings
        while(pt1<word.length() && pt2<abbr.length()){
            //if same chars
            if(word.charAt(pt1)==abbr.charAt(pt2)){
                pt1++;
                pt2++;
                continue;
            }
            //if start by 0 or different char
            if(abbr.charAt(pt2)=='0' || Character.isLetter(abbr.charAt(pt2))){
                return false;
            }
            //if valid numbers in abbr, skip chars in word
            int num = 0;
            while(pt2<abbr.length() && Character.isDigit(abbr.charAt(pt2))){
                num = num*10 + abbr.charAt(pt2) - '0';
                pt2++;
            }
            
            pt1+=num;
        }
        //return true if meet the requiremet, return false if not
        return pt1==word.length() && pt2==abbr.length();
    }
}
